<h3 class="text-center my-4">Interesting Facts About Bony Fishes in Tubbataha Reef</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Diversity of Species</h4>
    <p>Tubbataha Reef is one of the most biodiverse marine ecosystems in the world, with over 600 species of fish recorded. Many of these species are bony fishes, contributing to the reef's rich biodiversity.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Coral Reef Health Indicator</h4>
    <p>The presence of species like parrotfish and wrasses serves as an important indicator of coral reef health. These fishes help maintain the coral ecosystem by feeding on algae and preventing overgrowth.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Endemic Species</h4>
    <p>Some of the fish species found in Tubbataha Reef are endemic to the Philippines, meaning they are found nowhere else in the world. This makes Tubbataha a critical site for preserving marine biodiversity.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Role in the Ecosystem</h4>
    <p>Bony fishes in Tubbataha play essential roles as predators, prey, and herbivores. They help maintain balance by controlling algae growth, contributing to nutrient cycling, and serving as food for larger predators.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Threats to Bony Fishes in Tubbataha Reef</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Overfishing</h4>
    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/00/Chilean_purse_seine.jpg" alt="Overfishing" class="img-fluid img-thumbnail" style="max-width: 70%; height: auto;" />
    </div>
    <p>Despite Tubbataha being a protected area, illegal fishing and overfishing in surrounding waters continue to pose a threat to fish populations, including species like groupers and snappers.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Climate Change</h4>
    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <img src="https://www.un.org/sites/un2.un.org/files/2021/09/climatechange11.jpg" alt="ClimateChange" class="img-fluid img-thumbnail" style="max-width: 70%; height: auto;" />
    </div>
    <p>Rising sea temperatures and ocean acidification can lead to coral bleaching, reducing the availability of food and shelter for fish species in Tubbataha Reef.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Pollution</h4>
    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <img src="https://bloghart.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/20-Harmful-Effects-of-Water-Pollution-1.jpg" alt="Pollution" class="img-fluid img-thumbnail" style="max-width: 70%; height: auto;" />
    </div>
    <p>Pollution from plastics and chemicals can affect marine life. Though Tubbataha is remote, pollution from surrounding areas can still impact the reef ecosystem.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Habitat Degradation</h4>
    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <img src="https://www.sciencing.com/sciencing/destruction-marine-ecosystem-5777/8245e404b60c4352a4c3b255796bc5d1.jpg" alt="HabitatDegredation" class="img-fluid img-thumbnail" style="max-width: 70%; height: auto;" />
    </div>
    <p>While Tubbataha is a protected area, coral reefs throughout the Philippines face threats from unsustainable tourism, coastal development, and destructive fishing methods like blast fishing.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">5. Invasive Species</h4>
    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <img src="https://www.rmg.co.uk/sites/default/files/styles/max_width_1440/public/2022-11/Pterois_volitans_Manado-e_edit_0.jpg?itok=fdI4SiQN" alt="InvasiveSpecies" class="img-fluid img-thumbnail" style="max-width: 70%; height: auto;" />
    </div>
    <p>Non-native species, such as the crown-of-thorns starfish, can disrupt the reef ecosystem by preying on corals, impacting the habitats that bony fishes depend on.</p>
</section>


<h3 class="text-center my-4">Conservation Practices to Protect Bony Fishes</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Marine Protected Areas (MPAs)</h4>
    <p>Tubbataha Reef is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and a Marine Protected Area (MPA). Strengthening enforcement and protection efforts is crucial to preserving this pristine ecosystem.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Sustainable Fisheries</h4>
    <p>Promoting sustainable fishing practices in surrounding waters will help reduce pressure on fish populations, ensuring long-term sustainability for both the fish and their habitats.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Coral Restoration Programs</h4>
    <p>Supporting coral restoration programs can help rehabilitate degraded areas of the reef, providing better habitats for bony fishes and other marine life.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Pollution Control</h4>
    <p>Reducing plastic and chemical pollution in nearby waters is critical to maintaining a healthy ecosystem in Tubbataha and other coral reef systems.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">5. Climate Change Mitigation</h4>
    <p>Efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions can help slow the effects of climate change, protecting the long-term health of Tubbataha Reef and its marine inhabitants.</p>
</section>


